# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2011-nab-cup
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2011-nab-cup/1940-vfl-lightning-premiership] The **1940 VFL Lightning Premiership** (known at the time as the **Patriotic Premiership**) was an Australian rules football knockout competition played entirely on Saturday, 3 August 1940, at the Melbourne Cricket Ground (MCG).
[src:2011-nab-cup/1940-vfl-lightning-premiership] It was played during a week's break of the Victorian Football Leagues's 1940 season between Rounds 14 and 15.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1940-vfl-lightning-premiership] It was contested by the 12 teams who competed in the 1940 VFL season.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1940-vfl-lightning-premiership] A total of 30,407 witnessed the day's matches.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1940-vfl-lightning-premiership] St Kilda won the lighting premiership competition, defeating Richmond in the final by 24 points.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1940-vfl-lightning-premiership] It was the first premiership of any kind at any grade that the St Kilda Football Club had won in its history.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1940-vfl-lightning-premiership] This was the first time a lightning premiership had been contested in the VFL.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1940-vfl-lightning-premiership] The tournament was played to raise money for the Patriotic Fund during World War II; similar tournaments were held in other leagues, including the South Australian National Football League (SANFL), around the same time.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1940-vfl-lightning-premiership] The Patriotic Premiership was staged as a knock-out tournament amongst the twelve VFL teams on a single day.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1940-vfl-lightning-premiership] Because twelve teams is not enough for a balanced knock-out tournament, the draw was arranged such that the teams which occupied the bottom four places on the league ladder at the time of the tournament had an easier path to the final.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1940-vfl-lightning-premiership] Each match lasted for twenty minutes, without time-on, played in a single continuous period.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1941-vfl-lightning-premiership] The **1941 VFL Lightning Premiership** was an Australian rules football knockout competition played entirely on 24 May.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1941-vfl-lightning-premiership] It was played during a week's break of the Victorian Football Leagues's 1941 VFL season between rounds 4 and 5 with all games being played at the MCG.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1941-vfl-lightning-premiership] The competition was also played on the same day as an interstate match between New South Wales and Victoria in Sydney.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1941-vfl-lightning-premiership] This was the second time a lightning premiership had been contested in the VFL.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1941-vfl-lightning-premiership] It was contested by the 12 VFL teams who competed in the 1941 VFL season.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1941-vfl-lightning-premiership] A crowd of 19,572 attended the competition.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1941-vfl-lightning-premiership] Collingwood won the competition by 1 point, defeating Melbourne in the final.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1943-vfl-lightning-premiership] The **1943 VFL Lightning Premiership** was an Australian rules football knockout competition played entirely on Saturday 24, July.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1943-vfl-lightning-premiership] It was played during a week's break of the Victorian Football Leagues's 1943 VFL season between rounds 11 and 12, with all games being played at Princes Park.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1943-vfl-lightning-premiership] The competition was played as a wartime charities fundraiser between the league's top four clubs.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1943-vfl-lightning-premiership] This was the third time a lightning premiership had been contested in the VFL.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1943-vfl-lightning-premiership] Approximately 11,000 people attended the three match competition.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1943-vfl-lightning-premiership] Essendon won the competition by 8 points, defeating Fitzroy in the final.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1951-vfl-lightning-premiership] The **1951 VFL Lightning Premiership** was an Australian rules football knockout competition played entirely on Wednesday, 9 May.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1951-vfl-lightning-premiership] It was played on the Jubilee Day holiday, held to celebrate 50 years of Federation of Australia, between rounds 3 and 4 of the Victorian Football League's 1951 season with all games played at the MCG.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1951-vfl-lightning-premiership] This was the fourth time a lightning premiership had been contested in the VFL, the first since 1943.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1951-vfl-lightning-premiership] It was contested by the 12 VFL teams who competed in the 1951 VFL season.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1951-vfl-lightning-premiership] A total of 25,882 people attended the competition.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1951-vfl-lightning-premiership] Collingwood won its second Lighting Premiership competition defeating Melbourne in the final by 6 points.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1952-vfl-lightning-premiership] The **1952 VFL Lightning Premiership** was an Australian rules football knockout competition played entirely on Saturday, 24 May.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1952-vfl-lightning-premiership] It was played on the Empire Day holiday between rounds 5 and 6 of the Victorian Football League's 1952 season with all games played at the MCG.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1952-vfl-lightning-premiership] This was the fifth time a lightning premiership had been contested in the VFL.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1952-vfl-lightning-premiership] It was contested by the 12 VFL teams who competed in the 1952 VFL season.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1952-vfl-lightning-premiership] A total of 33,719 people attended the competition.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1952-vfl-lightning-premiership] Melbourne won its first Lighting Premiership competition defeating South Melbourne in the final by 7 points.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1953-vfl-lightning-premiership] The **1953 VFL Lightning Premiership** was an Australian rules football knockout competition played entirely on Tuesday, 2 June.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1953-vfl-lightning-premiership] It was played on the same day as Elizabeth II's Coronation between rounds 6 and 7 of the Victorian Football League's 1953 season with all games played at the MCG.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1953-vfl-lightning-premiership] This was the sixth time a Lightning premiership had been contested in the VFL.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1953-vfl-lightning-premiership] It was contested by the 12 VFL teams who competed in the 1953 VFL season.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1953-vfl-lightning-premiership] A total of 36,715 people attended the competition.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1953-vfl-lightning-premiership] Richmond won its first Lightning Premiership competition defeating St Kilda in the final by 14 points.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1956-night-series-cup] The **1956 VFL Night Premiership Cup** was the Victorian Football League end of season cup competition played between the eight teams that didn't make the finals of that season.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1956-night-series-cup] It was held between 23 August to 17 September 1956 with games being played at the Lake Oval, home ground of South Melbourne as it was the only ground equipped to host night games.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1956-night-series-cup] Eight teams played in the first competition with the final seeing an attendance of 32,450 as South Melbourne defeated Carlton in the final by 6 points (13.16.94 to 13.10.88).
[src:2011-nab-cup/1956-night-series-cup] The opening match of the 1956 edition saw South Melbourne record the first victory of the new competition by 20 points over St Kilda.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1956-night-series-cup] But the match was remembered for the brawl that happened in the third quarter which featured all of the players, umpires and some spectators in scenes not since the 1945 VFL Grand Final between Carlton and South Melbourne.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1956-night-series-cup] The following match which was played five days later saw a surprise victory by North Melbourne who defeated Essendon by two points with North Melbourne leading at every change to get the win.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1956-night-series-cup] Richmond and Carlton also recorded narrow wins over Hawthorn and Fitzroy in the remaining two quarter-finals which was played on 30 August and the 4 September.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1956-night-series-cup] The semi-finals began on the 6 September with South Melbourne taking on North Melbourne.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1956-night-series-cup] In another tight tussle between the teams, it was not until late on in the final quarter with the usage of the wind that South Melbourne would take the win with a goal from Monks sealing the five point victory.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1956-night-series-cup] In the second semi-final, an attendance of 25,500 saw Carlton win the match by 12 points in what *The Age* called fast, rugged and exciting football with Carlton leading at each break to record the victory.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1956-night-series-cup] The final of the 1956 edition was played on the 17 September 1956 between South Melbourne and Carlton.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1956-night-series-cup] With an attendance of 32,450 watching the match, South Melbourne's win was credited in the second quarter when they outscored Carlton 4.2 to 0.3 to open up a thirty-one point lead.
[src:2011-nab-cup/1956-night-series-cup] Carlton tried to come back into the match throughout the final quarter and had a chance to take the lead but a dropped pass from Hands would give South Melbourne the win by six points and become the first winners of the Night Series Cup.
[src:2011-nab-cup/2011-nab-cup] The **2011 NAB Cup** was the Australian Football League (AFL) pre-season competition played before the 2011 season.
[src:2011-nab-cup/2011-nab-cup] The games were played between 11 February and 11 March.
[src:2011-nab-cup/2011-nab-cup] The first match was between Adelaide and Melbourne in Adelaide at AAMI Stadium.
[src:2011-nab-cup/2011-nab-cup] This was the first time since 2003 that the competition format had changed.
[src:2011-nab-cup/2011-nab-cup] The first round fixtures were announced by the AFL on 26 October 2010.
[src:2011-nab-cup/2011-nab-cup] On 16 December 2010, the AFL announced the towns that will play host to the NAB Challenge competition.
[src:2011-nab-cup/2011-nab-cup] In week 1, the Adelaide suburb of Thebarton hosted an AFL pre-season game for the first time at Thebarton Oval where SANFL team Woodville-West Torrens plays.
[src:2011-nab-cup/2011-nab-cup] Traeger Park in Alice Springs, Manuka Oval, Visy Park and Skilled Stadium also hosted matches.
[src:2011-nab-cup/2011-nab-cup] Week 2 saw matches played at Lavington for the first time since 2006 as well as games at Southport, Bunbury, Shepparton, Visy Park and AAMI Stadium.
[src:2011-nab-cup/2011-nab-cup] In the final week of the competition, matches were played at Coffs Harbour, North Ballarat, Southport, Willaston near Gawler (SA), Fremantle, Aurora Stadium and Visy Park.
